1.Get employee name + manager name

SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m
ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;

2.Get user name,wallet balance,total transaction amount

SELECT u.name, w.balance, SUM(t.amount) AS total_amount
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN wallets w ON u.user_id = w.user_id
LEFT JOIN transactions t ON u.user_id = t.user_id
GROUP BY u.name, w.balance;

3.Users with both SUCCESS and FAILED

SELECT user_id
FROM transactions
GROUP BY user_id
HAVING 
    SUM(CASE WHEN status = 'SUCCESS' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) > 0
    AND
    SUM(CASE WHEN status = 'FAILED' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) > 0;


4.Users with transactions in >1 city

SELECT user_id
FROM transactions
GROUP BY user_id
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT city) > 1;

5.Why JOIN creates duplicates?

Because:
One row in table A can match multiple rows in table B
Example:

1 user → 5 transactions
JOIN result = 5 rows
This is called one-to-many relationship explosion


